"Mauritius and other countries discover their first cases of the new coronavirus variant Omicron strain - Xinhua News" 
"According to recent reports from Xinhua News, foreign correspondents have confirmed that Mauritius, Cyprus and Malawi have reported their first cases of infection with the new variant of the coronavirus Omicron strain." 
"Mauritius reported its first two cases of Omicron strain infection on February 10th." 
"As introduced by the Minister of Health, Kailash Jagutpah, one of the infected individuals is a tourist who arrived in Mauritius from South Africa on November 27th, while the other infected person is a local resident who tested positive for COVID-19 after coming into contact with someone who recently returned from South Africa on November 30th." 
"Both infected individuals have now tested negative for COVID-19 after receiving treatment and quarantine in the hospital, and have returned to their respective homes."
The Cyprus Ministry of Health announced on the 10th that the country has confirmed its first three cases of the Omicron strain of the virus.
These three people are students who returned from abroad at the beginning of the month and, due to their mild symptoms, were not hospitalized.
To prevent the spread of the Omicron strain, the Cypriot government is constantly increasing its preventive measures.
From December 6th to January 10th, all travelers over the age of 12 who enter the country by plane will be required to pay for a nucleic acid test at the airport.
The Cyprus Ministry of Health also announced on the 10th that they will begin vaccinating children aged 5 to 11 with the Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine.
"Malawi's Health Minister, Khumbize Chiponda, said on the 9th that the country has discovered its first 3 cases of Omika virus infection. 
The health department carried out genomic sequencing on 12 new positive samples collected from November 9th to December 2nd and found these 3 infected cases."